concept_explanation.pattern:
**Two Pointer pattern — when to use it:**

```
Use two pointers when:
1. Array is SORTED (or can be sorted)
2. You need to find a PAIR satisfying some condition
3. You want O(n) instead of O(n²) brute force

Two pointer types:
  INWARD: lo=0, hi=n-1, move toward each other
    When: pair problems, palindrome check, container water
  OUTWARD: both start at same point, expand
    When: expand-around-center (palindromes)
  SAME DIRECTION: slow=0, fast=0, fast moves ahead
    When: remove duplicates, find cycle, nth from end

Inward two pointer template:
  int lo = 0, hi = arr.length - 1;
  while (lo < hi) {
    if (condition_met(arr[lo], arr[hi])) {
      // record result, move both
      lo++; hi--;
    } else if (sum_too_small) {
      lo++;    // increase sum → move left pointer right
    } else {
      hi--;    // decrease sum → move right pointer left
    }
  }
```

concept_explanation.pair_sum_example:
**Pair sum — classic O(n) two-pointer:**

```java
// Given SORTED array, find if any pair sums to target
bool twoSum(int[] sorted, int target) {
    int lo = 0, hi = sorted.length - 1;
    while (lo < hi) {
        int sum = sorted[lo] + sorted[hi];
        if (sum == target) return true;      // found!
        else if (sum < target) lo++;         // need bigger sum
        else hi--;                            // need smaller sum
    }
    return false;
    // O(n) time — each step: lo++ or hi-- → at most n steps
    // O(1) space — two index variables only
}
// If array not sorted: sort first → O(n log n) total
```

